{"entity": "Cache", "type": "concept", "description": "Cache is a high-speed memory component designed to improve the performance and efficiency of computer systems by reducing data access times. It is typically located between the central processing unit (CPU) and the main memory, serving as an intermediary storage layer. Cache temporarily stores frequently accessed or recently used data, leveraging the principles of data and instruction locality to ensure faster retrieval and enhance overall system performance.\n\nThis type of memory is volatile and often built using semiconductor technology. Cache stores data in small, limited sections known as cache lines or blocks, which can be managed with policies such as direct mapping for efficient memory organization. It is capable of handling both data and instructions, ensuring synchronization with the main memory as needed. By maintaining copies of critical or frequently requested portions of the main memory, cache accelerates computing processes while minimizing the average access time.\n\nIn practice, cache is an integral part of modern computer systems, designed not only to improve the speed of the processor’s access to memory but also to optimize the overall efficiency of computing operations. This memory layer significantly contributes to the performance of a system by temporarily holding data that the processor might need to reference, thereby minimizing delays in data transfer.<SEP>Cache, within SSDs, is a high-speed memory system to enhance data processing performance.<SEP>Cache is a high-speed memory used to delay and group write operations, helping to extend the lifespan of Flash Memory.<SEP>Cache is a multi-level memory placed between CPU and DRAM to alleviate memory bottleneck issues.<SEP>Cache is a high-speed memory buffer that stores frequently accessed data, used as 64-bit cache lines in CDRAM.<SEP>Cache là bộ nhớ tạm thời dùng để lưu trữ dữ liệu truy cập thường xuyên, giúp cải thiện hiệu suất của VXL."}
{"entity": "Intelligent System", "type": "concept", "description": "Intelligent System is a technological concept built on the foundation of Artificial Intelligence, characterized by flexible, adaptive intelligence with key features such as memory, learning, dynamism, reasoning, and the ability to manage uncertain information. This enables computers to possess capabilities akin to human intelligence. In the context of Industry 4.0, Intelligent Systems are a main subject of discussion, encompassing various applications, challenges, and important issues. These systems are capable of understanding natural language, representing knowledge, performing automatic reasoning, and utilizing machine learning to adapt and extrapolate. Essentially, Intelligent Systems are designed to simulate human intelligence, making them a crucial component in the advancement of technology, particularly within the framework of Industry 4.0."}
{"entity": "Instruction Cache", "type": "concept", "description": "Instruction Cache is a type of cache memory dedicated to storing CPU instructions.<SEP>Instruction Cache is a separate part of Cache L1, dedicated to instructions."}
{"entity": "Cache Size", "type": "metric", "description": "Cache Size is the total amount of data that a cache can hold, influencing performance.<SEP>Cache Size refers to the storage capacity of cache memory, which impacts cost, system efficiency, and access speed.<SEP>Cache Size is the total memory size of the cache, calculated as k * 2."}
{"entity": "VXL", "type": "concept", "description": "VXL refers to the Central Processing Unit (CPU) or processor, a term frequently used as a Vietnamese abbreviation for this fundamental component within computing architecture. It serves as the central element responsible for executing instructions, performing various operations, and processing data as part of a computer's instruction cycle.\n\nThis processing unit is crucial for data execution and control tasks, including the execution of programs and dispatching commands to their respective I/O modules. The VXL actively communicates with these I/O modules, employing interrupt lines to receive interrupt requests and manage associated interrupt service routines.\n\nMoreover, the VXL exhibits capabilities in managing system resources and data transfers. It can safely perform alternative tasks while awaiting memory access requests from SDRAM. In the context of Direct Memory Access (DMA) operations, the VXL plays a role at both the initiation and conclusion of data transfers, and may temporarily relinquish bus control or be halted to facilitate DMA requirements.<SEP>VXL là viết tắt của Vi xử lý, đề cập đến thiết kế và kiến trúc của các bộ xử lý máy tính.<SEP>VXL is the computer system that executes the functions defined by the instruction set.<SEP>VXL (Vi xử lý) là phần cứng trung tâm thực hiện các loại hoạt động, bao gồm truyền dữ liệu, tính toán số học, và quản lý bộ nhớ.<SEP>VXL performs logic computation, conversion, control transfer, and I/O operations.<SEP>A processing unit that has a memory word size of 1 byte."}
{"entity": "Interconnection", "type": "concept", "description": "Interconnections link gates and memory cells within a computer."}
{"entity": "CPU", "type": "architecture", "description": "CPU is the fundamental component of a computer system, functioning as its core processor for executing instructions and processing data. It operates through the fetch-decode-execute cycle, retrieving instructions from memory, decoding them using opcodes, and performing operations with the Arithmetic Logic Unit (ALU). The CPU utilizes data buses, address buses, and control signal lines to communicate with memory and I/O modules, managing data flow and addresses. During processing, the CPU writes results to registers and coordinates information exchange with I/O modules through instruction decoding and status reporting.\n\nCPU actively manages system resources and controls I/O activities. It executes I/O commands by setting addresses on buses, sending control signals, and transferring data. It also monitors I/O module status and responds to interrupt signals, including interrupt handling involving priority selection, request finishing, and register restoration.  The processor participates in data transfer between I/O devices and memory using programmed I/O or interrupt-controlled methods, accommodating Direct Memory Access (DMA).\n\nPerformance can be limited when the CPU's speed exceeds main memory speed, causing delays during memory access requests. CPU accesses both memory and I/O devices, utilizing memory-mapped I/O configurations.  Through instruction execution, memory management, I/O coordination, and interrupt handling, the CPU orchestrates computational processes as the central processing unit of the computer system. CPU is responsible for fetching and executing instructions. CPU is the central processing unit that controls computer activities and performs data processing.  CPU is the central processing unit of the system."}
{"entity": "Cache Mapping", "type": "concept", "description": "Cache Mapping defines the assignment of main memory blocks to specific cache lines, examples include Direct Mapping, Associative Mapping, and Set-Associative Mapping.<SEP>Cache Mapping is the technique used to map main memory data to cache memory locations.<SEP>Cache Mapping refers to the technique used to place and retrieve data in the cache from main memory."}
{"entity": "Jump Instruction", "type": "concept", "description": "A control flow operation.<SEP>Jump Instruction is an unconditional control transfer that loads a specified address into the Program Counter (PC)."}
{"entity": "Word", "type": "concept", "description": "Word is a fundamental unit of data in computing, typically defined as a natural memory unit sized to match the bits used for representing integers and instruction lengths. Its size varies by architecture; for example, in Intel x86 systems, the word size is commonly 32 bits, while in the historic IAS computer, each word contained 40 binary bits. As a general concept, a word serves as a unit for storing data or instructions in memory and is transferred between registers and I/O ports.\n\nIn memory addressing, a word often functions as the smallest addressable unit in main memory or cache memory, though this depends on the system design. Within cache memory specifically, a word constitutes part of the memory address inside a cache line, used to identify precise data bytes or blocks. In associative mapping schemes, the word field in addresses frequently designates the exact data block within a cache line. Consequently, in the context of cache blocks, a word is regarded as the smallest unit of data fetched and processed, enhancing access efficiency.\n\nThus, while the term \"word\" broadly denotes a fixed-size data unit, its precise role—ranging from a basic storage element to a granular addressing component—adapts to architectural contexts, from general-purpose memory to specialized cache hierarchies.<SEP>Word là đơn vị dữ liệu cơ bản trong máy tính, thường có kích thước cố định.<SEP>Word is a data unit of 32 bits, corresponding to the 32b data size in ARM processors."}
{"entity": "Computer", "type": "concept", "description": "A Computer is a machine or system fundamentally designed to process information and execute programs. It is composed of various interconnected components, including gates, memory cells, and the connections between them, all configured to perform specific functions. As a device, a computer actively performs programs, encompassing activities such as instruction execution, interrupt handling, and input/output (I/O) operations.\n\nBeyond its foundational roles, a computer is the machine that Intelligent Systems leverage to acquire capabilities reminiscent of human intelligence, such as imitation, language understanding, thinking, and learning. Its design can feature a sophisticated processing unit, allowing even an advanced I/O module to function as a complete computer equipped with its own local memory. The nature of the computer has been significantly transformed by ongoing advancements in memory and processing technology, particularly throughout the decades following 1970. Therefore, its development history, design characteristics, and performance evaluation are important subjects of study.<SEP>Computer is a device that uses binary data, often in multiples of 4 bits, equivalent to a single hexadecimal digit.<SEP>Computer is involved in an interface with peripheral devices.<SEP>Computer is an electronic device that processes data according to instructions, consisting of CPU, memory, I/O, and system bus components.<SEP>A Computer is a machine for which the text discusses main functions and main components."}
{"entity": "Block Size", "type": "metric", "description": "Block Size refers to the size of a block in memory or cache, often measured in words or bytes.<SEP>Block Size is the amount of data, measured in words or bytes, contained in a single cache block or line.<SEP>Block Size refers to the size of the data block fetched and stored in the cache, impacting access rates and cache efficiency.<SEP>Block Size is the unit of data exchanged between cache and main memory, impacting cache efficiency."}
{"entity": "Data Locality", "type": "concept", "description": "Data Locality refers to the principle that data and instructions stored in memory tend to be accessed repeatedly within a short period of time or are situated close to one another in memory."}
{"entity": "Local Bus", "type": "concept", "description": "Local Bus connects the processor to the system bus through the cache, isolating the processor and memory, and allows for DMA operations.<SEP>Local Bus is a high-speed pathway dedicated to connecting specific internal components such as the processor and cache."}
{"entity": "Imitation", "type": "concept", "description": "Imitation is the capability of copying or mimicking behavior or actions, mentioned as a capability of human intelligence to be implemented in computers.<SEP>Imitation is the capability of copying or mimicking behavior or actions, mentioned as a capability of human intelligence to be implemented in computers."}
{"entity": "Unified Cache", "type": "concept", "description": "Unified Cache is a cache design where instructions and data are stored in the same cache, offering higher access speed and automatic balancing between loading instructions and data.<SEP>Unified Cache is a cache memory design that uses a single shared cache for both instructions and data."}
{"entity": "x86 Architecture", "type": "architecture", "description": "Computer architecture discussed as a topic in section 4 concerning computer development.<SEP>x86 Architecture is a widely used instruction set architecture that implements SIMD capabilities through instruction set extensions."}
{"entity": "I/O Module", "type": "concept", "description": "The I/O Module is a crucial hardware component in computing systems responsible for managing input and output operations. It serves as an interface that facilitates communication between the processor (CPU) and peripheral devices, allowing for data transfer between them. The I/O Module handles both data and instruction input, displaying output results, and ensuring that the processor can effectively communicate with a variety of I/O devices.\n\nThis module is responsible for several key functions, including transmitting control information, data, and addresses between the CPU and peripheral devices. It manages the input/output operations by controlling traffic flow between internal components and external devices, as well as executing input/output tasks and signaling the processor upon task completion. The I/O Module is typically slower than the CPU, which can introduce processing delays.\n\nAdditionally, the I/O Module operates by receiving commands from the CPU, reading data from I/O devices, managing interrupts, and placing data on the system bus. It uses internal buffers to facilitate efficient communication and may directly exchange data with the main memory through Direct Memory Access (DMA). The module also generates interrupt requests, which alert the CPU when data operations are necessary, and it responds to probe commands while managing the system's interrupt handling through various setups, such as the Daisy Chain.\n\nAs technology evolves, the I/O Module may incorporate advanced capabilities, including its own processing functions and local memory, enabling it to operate increasingly autonomously. Overall, the I/O Module is an essential component that plays a vital role in the smooth operation of computer systems by managing the interactions between the CPU and peripheral devices effectively.<SEP>I/O Module is the corresponding input/output module for an I/O device, specified in the instruction to access the device.<SEP>I/O Module is a component that interfaces with external devices to manage input and output operations of the system."}
{"entity": "Protocol Layer", "type": "concept", "description": "The Protocol Layer in the QPI architecture defines rules for exchanging data packets, which include a fixed number of Flits.<SEP>Protocol Layer is responsible for managing communication processes and ensuring proper operation of network functions."}
{"entity": "DMA", "type": "concept", "description": "DMA, or Direct Memory Access, is a data transfer method that enables Input/Output (I/O) modules to exchange data directly with memory, bypassing the central processing unit (CPU). This capability allows for efficient and high-speed data transfers between peripheral devices and memory, significantly improving overall system efficiency by reducing the involvement of the CPU during these transactions.\n\nThe DMA mechanism facilitates memory transfers where devices can send and receive data directly to and from memory, thereby allowing CPU resources to be allocated to other processes. It reduces the need for the CPU to manage these data transfers continuously, which can be particularly advantageous during operations that require extensive input/output processing. This process typically involves an additional module on the bus system, which assumes control over data transmission and reception, thereby allowing the CPU to pause during the transfer cycles. \n\nIn practical terms, the DMA process includes the ability of peripherals to communicate effectively with memory, generating a system that minimizes bus cycles and enhances the performance of computational tasks. Overall, Direct Memory Access serves as a crucial technique for modern computing systems, streamlining data handling between various components.<SEP>DMA (Direct Memory Access) is a mechanism that allows peripherals to communicate with the system memory independently of the CPU."}
