{"entity1": "CPU", "entity2": "I/O Module", "description": "The relation (CPU, I/O Module) describes the functional interface and communication pathway between a central processing unit (CPU) and an input/output (I/O) module. The I/O module serves as a critical interface, connecting the CPU to peripheral devices and managing all data input and output operations. Communication between the two components is bidirectional, involving the exchange of control information, data, and addresses. The CPU reads from and writes to the I/O module during data operations, initiating actions by sending commands such as READ to start I/O tasks.\n\nA key mechanism for coordinating this interaction is interrupt-driven processing. The I/O module sends interrupt signal requests to the CPU to demand its attention, typically after data has been loaded into its data register and it is ready for transfer. Upon receiving an interrupt, the CPU processes the request. Alternatively, the CPU may periodically poll or check the status of the I/O module. In a typical handshake sequence, the CPU sends a data request signal to the I/O module, which then places the requested data onto the system bus for the CPU to read. Beyond data transfer, the I/O module is also involved in instruction decoding and status reporting back to the CPU.\n\nA significant characteristic of this relationship is the inherent speed disparity between the components; the CPU operates at a much faster speed than the I/O module. This difference can lead to wasted processing cycles for the CPU while it waits for slower I/O operations to complete, highlighting a classic performance bottleneck in computer architecture."}
