{"entity": "Cache", "type": "concept", "description": "Cache is a high-speed memory component designed to improve the performance and efficiency of computer systems by reducing data access times. It is typically located between the central processing unit (CPU) and the main memory, serving as an intermediary storage layer. Cache temporarily stores frequently accessed or recently used data, leveraging the principles of data and instruction locality to ensure faster retrieval and enhance overall system performance.\n\nThis type of memory is volatile and often built using semiconductor technology. Cache stores data in small, limited sections known as cache lines or blocks, which can be managed with policies such as direct mapping for efficient memory organization. It is capable of handling both data and instructions, ensuring synchronization with the main memory as needed. By maintaining copies of critical or frequently requested portions of the main memory, cache accelerates computing processes while minimizing the average access time.\n\nIn practice, cache is an integral part of modern computer systems, designed not only to improve the speed of the processor’s access to memory but also to optimize the overall efficiency of computing operations. This memory layer significantly contributes to the performance of a system by temporarily holding data that the processor might need to reference, thereby minimizing delays in data transfer.<SEP>Cache, within SSDs, is a high-speed memory system to enhance data processing performance.<SEP>Cache is a high-speed memory used to delay and group write operations, helping to extend the lifespan of Flash Memory.<SEP>Cache is a multi-level memory placed between CPU and DRAM to alleviate memory bottleneck issues.<SEP>Cache is a high-speed memory buffer that stores frequently accessed data, used as 64-bit cache lines in CDRAM.<SEP>Cache là bộ nhớ tạm thời dùng để lưu trữ dữ liệu truy cập thường xuyên, giúp cải thiện hiệu suất của VXL."}
