{"entity": "Computer Architecture", "type": "architecture", "description": "Computer Architecture is a fundamental discipline in computing that encompasses the design, structure, and organization of computer systems and their internal components. This field focuses on how various hardware elements interact and work together to form a cohesive computing system, including central processing units (CPU), memory hierarchy, input/output mechanisms, and bus connections that facilitate data transfer between components.\n\nFrom a functional perspective, Computer Architecture defines the essential attributes and characteristics visible to programmers that directly impact program execution. These include the instruction set architecture, data representation formats, memory addressing modes, and I/O mechanisms. The discipline emphasizes programmer-visible attributes that ensure correct system operation while optimizing performance and efficiency.\n\nAs an academic subject commonly designated as CSE370, Computer Architecture serves as a mandatory course covering the organization and structure of computer systems. The field integrates fundamental design principles that guide the creation and optimization of computer systems, making it a foundational concept in computing engineering disciplines. Understanding computer architecture enables professionals to design more efficient systems by comprehending both the structural organization and operational principles that govern modern computing technologies."}
