{"entity": "ALU", "type": "concept", "description": "The Arithmetic Logic Unit (ALU) is a fundamental hardware component prominently featured within a computer's Central Processing Unit (CPU) or processor. Functioning as an arithmetic and logic computation block, its primary responsibility is to execute all arithmetic operations, such as addition and subtraction, as well as logical operations like AND, OR, and NOT.\n\nBeyond its core computational duties, the ALU also plays a critical role in data integrity by detecting overflow conditions during operations. Upon detection, it signals the CPU to discard any potentially erroneous results. The ALU is widely recognized as a core component, sometimes serving as an alternative designation for the Integer Unit.\n\nRegarding data handling, the output results generated by the ALU can be directly forwarded or fed into an input register by a hardware unit. While this direct feeding mechanism is integral to processor efficiency, it can also contribute to systems that lead to data conflicts. The ALU's significance is universal, appearing as a distinct component dedicated to arithmetic and logic operations, for example, within the ARM architecture.<SEP>ALU (Arithmetic Logic Unit) là phần của VXL thực hiện các phép toán số học và logic.<SEP>ALU (Arithmetic and Logic Unit) performs data processing functions."}
