{"entity": "Registers", "type": "concept", "description": "Registers are small, high-speed storage locations within a computer processor or CPU, functioning as a type of memory used to temporarily hold data and instructions during execution. They serve as temporary storage components, often holding data before it is sent to the Arithmetic Logic Unit (ALU) for processing, and are integral to efficient data handling in computer systems. Registers are on-chip memory that can be referenced by instructions and have specific functions, such as acting as location types for operands. In certain architectures like ARM, registers are homogeneous, with operations performed directly on operands stored in them. Additionally, some registers are reserved for exclusive use in privileged modes, and during interrupt service, their contents may be saved to RAM to preserve system state. Overall, registers are essential processor storage units that facilitate rapid data access and manipulation during computational tasks.<SEP>Registers provide internal storage for the CPU."}
