{"entity": "Immediate Addressing", "type": "concept", "description": "Immediate Addressing is a mode where the operand is a constant value included directly in the instruction.<SEP>Immediate Addressing is the simplest form of addressing where the operand is the direct value. It can be used to define constants and set initial values for variables, requiring only one memory access to fetch the instruction. Its main disadvantage is that the size of the number is limited by the address field size.<SEP>Immediate Addressing is a method of addressing where the operand value is directly specified within the instruction itself."}
