{"entity": "VXL", "type": "concept", "description": "VXL refers to the Central Processing Unit (CPU) or processor, a term frequently used as a Vietnamese abbreviation for this fundamental component within computing architecture. It serves as the central element responsible for executing instructions, performing various operations, and processing data as part of a computer's instruction cycle.\n\nThis processing unit is crucial for data execution and control tasks, including the execution of programs and dispatching commands to their respective I/O modules. The VXL actively communicates with these I/O modules, employing interrupt lines to receive interrupt requests and manage associated interrupt service routines.\n\nMoreover, the VXL exhibits capabilities in managing system resources and data transfers. It can safely perform alternative tasks while awaiting memory access requests from SDRAM. In the context of Direct Memory Access (DMA) operations, the VXL plays a role at both the initiation and conclusion of data transfers, and may temporarily relinquish bus control or be halted to facilitate DMA requirements.<SEP>VXL là viết tắt của Vi xử lý, đề cập đến thiết kế và kiến trúc của các bộ xử lý máy tính.<SEP>VXL is the computer system that executes the functions defined by the instruction set.<SEP>VXL (Vi xử lý) là phần cứng trung tâm thực hiện các loại hoạt động, bao gồm truyền dữ liệu, tính toán số học, và quản lý bộ nhớ.<SEP>VXL performs logic computation, conversion, control transfer, and I/O operations.<SEP>A processing unit that has a memory word size of 1 byte."}
{"entity": "Fetch", "type": "concept", "description": "Fetch is a stage where the next instruction is read from memory into the microprocessor."}
{"entity": "CPU", "type": "architecture", "description": "CPU is the fundamental component of a computer system, functioning as its core processor for executing instructions and processing data. It operates through the fetch-decode-execute cycle, retrieving instructions from memory, decoding them using opcodes, and performing operations with the Arithmetic Logic Unit (ALU). The CPU utilizes data buses, address buses, and control signal lines to communicate with memory and I/O modules, managing data flow and addresses. During processing, the CPU writes results to registers and coordinates information exchange with I/O modules through instruction decoding and status reporting.\n\nCPU actively manages system resources and controls I/O activities. It executes I/O commands by setting addresses on buses, sending control signals, and transferring data. It also monitors I/O module status and responds to interrupt signals, including interrupt handling involving priority selection, request finishing, and register restoration.  The processor participates in data transfer between I/O devices and memory using programmed I/O or interrupt-controlled methods, accommodating Direct Memory Access (DMA).\n\nPerformance can be limited when the CPU's speed exceeds main memory speed, causing delays during memory access requests. CPU accesses both memory and I/O devices, utilizing memory-mapped I/O configurations.  Through instruction execution, memory management, I/O coordination, and interrupt handling, the CPU orchestrates computational processes as the central processing unit of the computer system. CPU is responsible for fetching and executing instructions. CPU is the central processing unit that controls computer activities and performs data processing.  CPU is the central processing unit of the system."}
{"entity": "Memory", "type": "concept", "description": "Memory is a critical hardware component within computer systems, primarily responsible for the storage and retrieval of data and instructions necessary for processing. As the main storage system for data and programs, Memory allows efficient access for other system components, particularly the Central Processing Unit (CPU) and the Arithmetic Logic Unit (ALU). It encompasses both program instructions and data, which are stored together in an organized manner, typically in addressable locations structured in units of bytes.\n\nMemory is essential in the execution of tasks within intelligent systems as it facilitates both the storage and retrieval functions required to execute processes harmoniously. It operates by maintaining variables and operands, such as X and Y, which are critical for computational instructions. Specific architectures, like the IAS computer, may define memory in terms of a certain number of words, emphasizing its role in including a range of storage categories such as registers, cache memory, and main memory. Access to Memory by the CPU is conducted via dedicated registers, including the Memory Address Register and Memory Buffer Register, enabling read and write operations.\n\nDuring processing, Memory plays a pivotal role in the fetch stage of the instruction cycle, where instructions are read into the microprocessor. Its interaction extends to input/output (I/O) operations, often facilitating data transfer through mechanisms such as Direct Memory Access (DMA). Additionally, specialized areas within Memory can contain privileged regions that are safeguarded by memory protection keys, ensuring security and stability in data handling. Overall, Memory stands as a fundamental component in managing and facilitating data operations throughout the broader computing environment.<SEP>Memory là thiết bị lưu trữ dữ liệu trong bộ nhớ.<SEP>Memory là thiết bị lưu trữ dữ liệu trong bộ nhớ.<SEP>Memory là bộ nhớ, với dung lượng 640GB trong NVIDIA HGX A100 640GB."}
{"entity": "Register Addressing", "type": "concept", "description": "Register Addressing is a mode where the operand is stored in a specified processor register.<SEP>Register Addressing is a method where the address field in an instruction refers to a register rather than a main memory address. It requires a small address field and avoids main memory references but results in a limited address space.<SEP>Register Addressing is a method of addressing where the operand is located in a general-purpose register."}
