{"entity": "Instruction", "type": "concept", "description": "Instruction, in computer science, refers to a fundamental command or single operation that forms part of a computer program and is executed by a processor or Central Processing Unit (CPU). It represents the basic unit of a computer program, communicating the desired operation to the CPU for processing.\n\nInstructions are stored in computer memory as binary codes and are represented as binary bit strings, often divided into various fields corresponding to different command components. A primary component is the operation code (opcode), which specifies the particular operation to be performed. Instructions can also contain an address field, which may include memory addresses, references to registers, or specifications for I/O device and module addresses. This address field can serve as a base for calculating the effective address, especially in relative addressing. Operands, which are the data on which the operation is executed, are another crucial part, either directly referenced within the instruction itself (as in immediate addressing) or indicated by source and result operand references. Some instructions may also include a reference to the next instruction. The number of addresses an instruction contains can vary, influencing its overall size.\n\nThe lifecycle of an instruction typically involves several stages, commencing with the Fetch stage where the instruction is read from memory into the microprocessor. An instruction can be in various states, such as being about to be fetched, currently being fetched, or awaiting execution. If a Control Hazard occurs due to an incorrect branch prediction during fetching, the subsequently fetched instructions are discarded to maintain proper program flow. The Program Counter Register usually manages the implicit access to the next instruction to be executed."}
{"entity": "I/O Module", "type": "concept", "description": "The I/O Module is a crucial hardware component in computing systems responsible for managing input and output operations. It serves as an interface that facilitates communication between the processor (CPU) and peripheral devices, allowing for data transfer between them. The I/O Module handles both data and instruction input, displaying output results, and ensuring that the processor can effectively communicate with a variety of I/O devices.\n\nThis module is responsible for several key functions, including transmitting control information, data, and addresses between the CPU and peripheral devices. It manages the input/output operations by controlling traffic flow between internal components and external devices, as well as executing input/output tasks and signaling the processor upon task completion. The I/O Module is typically slower than the CPU, which can introduce processing delays.\n\nAdditionally, the I/O Module operates by receiving commands from the CPU, reading data from I/O devices, managing interrupts, and placing data on the system bus. It uses internal buffers to facilitate efficient communication and may directly exchange data with the main memory through Direct Memory Access (DMA). The module also generates interrupt requests, which alert the CPU when data operations are necessary, and it responds to probe commands while managing the system's interrupt handling through various setups, such as the Daisy Chain.\n\nAs technology evolves, the I/O Module may incorporate advanced capabilities, including its own processing functions and local memory, enabling it to operate increasingly autonomously. Overall, the I/O Module is an essential component that plays a vital role in the smooth operation of computer systems by managing the interactions between the CPU and peripheral devices effectively.<SEP>I/O Module is the corresponding input/output module for an I/O device, specified in the instruction to access the device.<SEP>I/O Module is a component that interfaces with external devices to manage input and output operations of the system."}
