{"entity": "Microprocessor", "type": "concept", "description": "The Microprocessor is an integrated circuit that contains all the functions and components of a central processing unit (CPU) on a single chip. Serving as the central processing unit of a computer, it is a small-sized processor developed using integrated circuit technology. Its fundamental roles include reading instructions from memory, decoding opcodes, performing various operations, saving the current program state, and serving interrupt requests.\n\nThis computing component also facilitates interaction with other parts of a system, such as exchanging data with memory devices like RDRAM and communicating with I/O modules by receiving status information and issuing control commands. Historically, microprocessors were commonly found in older systems that frequently employed Fixed-Point Number representation. Specific examples, like the Microprocessor (VXL), have been characterized with configurations such as a 32-bit width and a 16-bit data bus.<SEP>The Microprocessor (VXL) is the component that executes commands and must be in a privileged state for system control commands."}
