{"entity": "Word", "type": "concept", "description": "Word is a fundamental unit of data in computing, typically defined as a natural memory unit sized to match the bits used for representing integers and instruction lengths. Its size varies by architecture; for example, in Intel x86 systems, the word size is commonly 32 bits, while in the historic IAS computer, each word contained 40 binary bits. As a general concept, a word serves as a unit for storing data or instructions in memory and is transferred between registers and I/O ports.\n\nIn memory addressing, a word often functions as the smallest addressable unit in main memory or cache memory, though this depends on the system design. Within cache memory specifically, a word constitutes part of the memory address inside a cache line, used to identify precise data bytes or blocks. In associative mapping schemes, the word field in addresses frequently designates the exact data block within a cache line. Consequently, in the context of cache blocks, a word is regarded as the smallest unit of data fetched and processed, enhancing access efficiency.\n\nThus, while the term \"word\" broadly denotes a fixed-size data unit, its precise role—ranging from a basic storage element to a granular addressing component—adapts to architectural contexts, from general-purpose memory to specialized cache hierarchies.<SEP>Word là đơn vị dữ liệu cơ bản trong máy tính, thường có kích thước cố định.<SEP>Word is a data unit of 32 bits, corresponding to the 32b data size in ARM processors."}
