{"entity": "ARM", "type": "architecture", "description": "ARM (Advanced RISC Machine) is a family of computer processor architectures that encompasses instruction set architectures (ISAs) known for their efficiency and low power consumption. As a Reduced Instruction Set Computer (RISC) system, ARM features a uniform register set, load/store architecture model, fixed-length instructions, separate ALU and shifter units, and a limited addressing mode scheme. The architecture is widely deployed in embedded systems and mobile devices due to its energy efficiency and performance optimization.\n\nARM processors support multiple data types including 8-bit, 16-bit, and 32-bit variants in both unsigned and two's complement formats. While traditional ARM implementations lack hardware floating-point support and require software implementation, the architecture enables conditional instruction execution based on processor status flags. Additionally, ARM supports both little-endian and big-endian data formats through endian conversion capabilities. These characteristics make ARM architectures particularly suitable for applications requiring power efficiency and compact processor designs."}
